<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="80" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1367,2004]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1404,1428]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">Etymology.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[342,440,1405,1428]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Memoan" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[342,440,1405,1428]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">Memoan</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, an Amerindian name for firefly reported by the portuguese explorer Gabriel Soares de Souza (
<number box="[235,296,1439,1463]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" value="1587.0">1587</number>
). It is derived from 
<emphasis box="[520,620,1441,1464]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">Mamoan</emphasis>
, which means firefly in indigenous Tupi-Guarani language (Papavero 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">et al</emphasis>
., 
<number box="[194,255,1476,1500]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" value="2009.0">2009</number>
). Gender male.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="80" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1367,2004]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1511,1536]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Frons with antennal sockets obliquely inserted on tubercles (
<figureCitation box="[1007,1080,1511,1535]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 3" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1823,1846]" captionTargetBox="[174,1391,223,1780]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,195,1830]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 3. Memoan ciceroi gen. et sp. nov., holotype male from Estação Biológica Santa Lúcia, Santa Teresa, Espírito Santo, Brazil: 1, habitus dorsal; 2, habitus ventral; 3, head, frontal view, which shows the fusion of the fronto-clypeus and the labrum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/283658/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">
FIG. 
<number box="[1065,1080,1511,1535]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
); antennae subserrate (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 3" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1823,1846]" captionTargetBox="[174,1391,223,1780]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,195,1830]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 3. Memoan ciceroi gen. et sp. nov., holotype male from Estação Biológica Santa Lúcia, Santa Teresa, Espírito Santo, Brazil: 1, habitus dorsal; 2, habitus ventral; 3, head, frontal view, which shows the fusion of the fronto-clypeus and the labrum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/283658/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">
FIGS 
<number pageId="1" pageNumber="80" value="1.5" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="1.0">1– 2</number>
</figureCitation>
), antenommeres II–IX compressed; labial palp one-segmented and obconic (
<figureCitation box="[1086,1167,1548,1572]" captionStart="FIGURES 4 – 5" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1934,1957]" captionTargetBox="[200,1390,230,1909]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[179,1408,181,1935]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 4 – 5. Memoan ciceroi gen. nov. et sp. nov.: 4, head and thorax, ventral. Note the subcontiguous eyes and the conspicuous sutures between mesosternum and mesanepisternum, and between the mesanepisternum and mesanepimerum. 5, Mouthparts. Note the one-segmented labial palps." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/283659/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">
FIG. 
<number box="[1151,1167,1548,1572]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
); pronotum and elytra alveolate (
<figureCitation box="[267,380,1583,1607]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 1 – 3" captionStart-1="FIGURES 4 – 5" captionStart-2="FIGURES 6 – 8" captionStartId-0="3.[151,264,1823,1846]" captionStartId-1="4.[151,264,1934,1957]" captionStartId-2="5.[151,264,1514,1537]" captionTargetBox-0="[174,1391,223,1780]" captionTargetBox-1="[200,1390,230,1909]" captionTargetBox-2="[187,1397,226,1452]" captionTargetId-0="figure@3.[151,1436,195,1830]" captionTargetId-1="figure@4.[179,1408,181,1935]" captionTargetId-2="figure@5.[151,1436,193,1493]" captionTargetPageId-0="3" captionTargetPageId-1="4" captionTargetPageId-2="5" captionText-0="FIGURES 1 – 3. Memoan ciceroi gen. et sp. nov., holotype male from Estação Biológica Santa Lúcia, Santa Teresa, Espírito Santo, Brazil: 1, habitus dorsal; 2, habitus ventral; 3, head, frontal view, which shows the fusion of the fronto-clypeus and the labrum." captionText-1="FIGURES 4 – 5. Memoan ciceroi gen. nov. et sp. nov.: 4, head and thorax, ventral. Note the subcontiguous eyes and the conspicuous sutures between mesosternum and mesanepisternum, and between the mesanepisternum and mesanepimerum. 5, Mouthparts. Note the one-segmented labial palps." captionText-2="FIGURES 6 – 8. Memoan ciceroi gen. nov. et sp. nov.: 6, apical antennomeres. Note the fusion between the two apical-most antennomeres. 7, pronotum and elytral base, dorsal. Note the deep punctuation all along the pronotum, scutellum and elytra; and the pronotal parassagital, posterior elevations. 8, right wing." httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/283658/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/283659/files/figure.png" httpUri-2="https://zenodo.org/record/283660/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">
FIGS 
<number box="[336,380,1583,1607]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" value="3.5" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="1.0">1–6</number>
</figureCitation>
); pleuroventral suture (between mesanepisternum and mesosternum) conspicuous (
<figureCitation box="[1312,1387,1583,1607]" captionStart="FIGURES 4 – 5" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1934,1957]" captionTargetBox="[200,1390,230,1909]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[179,1408,181,1935]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 4 – 5. Memoan ciceroi gen. nov. et sp. nov.: 4, head and thorax, ventral. Note the subcontiguous eyes and the conspicuous sutures between mesosternum and mesanepisternum, and between the mesanepisternum and mesanepimerum. 5, Mouthparts. Note the one-segmented labial palps." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/283659/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">
FIG. 
<number box="[1370,1387,1583,1607]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="81" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1367,2004]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,422,1619,1644]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">Description. Head</emphasis>
. (
<figureCitation box="[450,568,1620,1644]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 1 – 3" captionStart-1="FIGURES 4 – 5" captionStart-2="FIGURES 6 – 8" captionStartId-0="3.[151,264,1823,1846]" captionStartId-1="4.[151,264,1934,1957]" captionStartId-2="5.[151,264,1514,1537]" captionTargetBox-0="[174,1391,223,1780]" captionTargetBox-1="[200,1390,230,1909]" captionTargetBox-2="[187,1397,226,1452]" captionTargetId-0="figure@3.[151,1436,195,1830]" captionTargetId-1="figure@4.[179,1408,181,1935]" captionTargetId-2="figure@5.[151,1436,193,1493]" captionTargetPageId-0="3" captionTargetPageId-1="4" captionTargetPageId-2="5" captionText-0="FIGURES 1 – 3. Memoan ciceroi gen. et sp. nov., holotype male from Estação Biológica Santa Lúcia, Santa Teresa, Espírito Santo, Brazil: 1, habitus dorsal; 2, habitus ventral; 3, head, frontal view, which shows the fusion of the fronto-clypeus and the labrum." captionText-1="FIGURES 4 – 5. Memoan ciceroi gen. nov. et sp. nov.: 4, head and thorax, ventral. Note the subcontiguous eyes and the conspicuous sutures between mesosternum and mesanepisternum, and between the mesanepisternum and mesanepimerum. 5, Mouthparts. Note the one-segmented labial palps." captionText-2="FIGURES 6 – 8. Memoan ciceroi gen. nov. et sp. nov.: 6, apical antennomeres. Note the fusion between the two apical-most antennomeres. 7, pronotum and elytral base, dorsal. Note the deep punctuation all along the pronotum, scutellum and elytra; and the pronotal parassagital, posterior elevations. 8, right wing." httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/283658/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/283659/files/figure.png" httpUri-2="https://zenodo.org/record/283660/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">
FIGS 
<number box="[525,568,1620,1644]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" value="4.0" valueMax="7.0" valueMin="1.0">1–7</number>
</figureCitation>
) Completely covered by pronotum. Frons strongly tuberculate, tubercles contiguous. Vertex plane. Eyes large, as wide as half of pronotal anterior opening, approximate ventrally, with the distance between ventral margins smaller than pedicel length; dorsal margins subparallel. Antennal sockets obliquely inserted on tubercles, distance between the sockets shorter than socket diameter. Antennae elevenjointed, antenommeres III–IX compressed and serrate, X–XI fused and cylindrical. Mouthparts subprognathous. Labrum connate to fronto-clypeus, clypeolabral suture indistinct. Mandibles falcate, acuminated apically. Labial palp one-segmented, obconic. Gular sutures and tentorial pits contiguous.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1367,2004]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1436,151,1112]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="81" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,288,1872,1896]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">Thorax</emphasis>
. (
<figureCitation box="[313,401,1871,1895]" captionStart="FIGURES 4 – 5" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1934,1957]" captionTargetBox="[200,1390,230,1909]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[179,1408,181,1935]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 4 – 5. Memoan ciceroi gen. nov. et sp. nov.: 4, head and thorax, ventral. Note the subcontiguous eyes and the conspicuous sutures between mesosternum and mesanepisternum, and between the mesanepisternum and mesanepimerum. 5, Mouthparts. Note the one-segmented labial palps." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/283659/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">FIGS 4</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[417,460,1871,1895]" captionStart="FIGURES 6 – 8" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1514,1537]" captionTargetBox="[187,1397,226,1452]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,193,1493]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 6 – 8. Memoan ciceroi gen. nov. et sp. nov.: 6, apical antennomeres. Note the fusion between the two apical-most antennomeres. 7, pronotum and elytral base, dorsal. Note the deep punctuation all along the pronotum, scutellum and elytra; and the pronotal parassagital, posterior elevations. 8, right wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/283660/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">
7– 
<number box="[447,460,1871,1895]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" value="8.0">8</number>
</figureCitation>
) Pronotum wider than long, with sides slightly divergent posteriorly; alveolate with irregular, deep punctures, except by elevated, medially constrained areas; Prosternum with posterior process truncated posteriad, with width at base greater than prosternum length. Elytra six times longer than wide; humeri prominent and rounded, four rudimentary costae; with dense and widespread deep punctures; with bristles emerging from a globular base, and a sparse, minute pale vestiture (
<number box="[923,970,151,175]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" value="200.0">200</number>
x); epipleura narrow, nearly 
<number box="[1289,1299,151,175]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number box="[1310,1325,151,175]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" value="5.0">5</number>
of elytral width. Wings with complete radial cell, and reduced crossveins; bifurcate MP 
<number box="[1020,1032,188,212]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" value="3.0">3</number>
+ 
<number box="[1048,1063,188,212]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" value="4.0">4</number>
; C with stout setae. Pleuroventral suture (between mesanepisternum and mesosternum) conspicuous. Prosternum transverse. Suture between mesanepisternum and mesepimeron conspicuous. Median line of metasternum reaching mesosternum. Legs with pro and mesotrochantin bristled; prosternal coxae oblong, inclined obliquely; bristled anteriad, laterally glabrous; without tibial spurs; tarsomeres I–IV decreasing in length apically, the fourth bilobate; with paired simple claws.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,151,1112]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,316,367,392]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">Abdomen</emphasis>
. (
<figureCitation box="[337,463,367,391]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 13" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1877,1900]" captionTargetBox="[201,1366,307,1828]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[183,1410,269,1864]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 13. Memoan ciceroi gen. nov. et sp. nov.: 9, abdomen, left lateral; 10 abdomen, ventral (anterior end to left of page). 11, Detail of the abdomen, dorsal (arrows shows the dorsal spiracles); 12, aedeagal sheath: sintergite, dorsal and sternite IX, ventral (anterior ends to bottom of page). 13, aedeagus, dorsal." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/283661/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">
FIGS 
<number box="[406,463,367,391]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" value="11.0" valueMax="13.0" valueMin="9.0">9–13</number>
</figureCitation>
) Eight visible ventrites (abdominal sternites II–IX); lanterns on the ventrites V and VI; spiracles dorsal; posterolateral margins of terga produced and acute. Pygidium trilobate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1331,439,464]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,151,1112]" box="[199,1331,439,464]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,295,439,464]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">Biology.</emphasis>
Nocturnal, continuously glowing. They emanate a sweet scent, similar to marzipan frosting.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="81" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,151,1112]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,476,500]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">Remarks.</emphasis>
McDermott’s key to 
<taxonomicName box="[559,694,476,500]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Lampyridae</taxonomicName>
tribes would lead 
<taxonomicName box="[907,1005,477,500]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Memoan" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[907,1005,477,500]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">Memoan</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to 
<taxonomicName box="[1043,1146,476,500]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Photinini">Photinini</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[1162,1304,476,500]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Lampyrinae">Lampyrinae</taxonomicName>
), because it has “simple” mandibles (falcate, gradually tapering to apex), dorsal spiracles, “simple” antennae (filiform or serrate, compressed or not), and a scarse secondary pubescence, although notably scarcer than the typical dense vestiture of 
<taxonomicName box="[285,391,583,607]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Photinini">Photinini</taxonomicName>
. However, the new genus has characteristics rare or absent in 
<taxonomicName box="[1085,1190,583,607]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Photinini">Photinini</taxonomicName>
, but common to other lampyrids, like the 
<taxonomicName box="[367,504,620,644]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Amydetinae">Amydetinae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[559,699,620,644]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Lampyrinae">Lampyrinae</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName box="[709,874,620,644]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Cratomorphini">Cratomorphini</taxonomicName>
(see 
<tableCitation box="[933,1015,620,644]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,239,1160,1184]" captionTargetBox="[159,1422,1211,1871]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="TABLE 1. Shared similarities and sub-familial assignment of Memoan and other cited genera on the item Remarks." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/80FF6604FFD0FFDDFF3B58A1CD51FB39" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" tableUuid="80FF6604FFD0FFDDFF3B58A1CD51FB39">
Table 
<number box="[1002,1015,620,644]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" value="1.0">1</number>
</tableCitation>
). The fused distal antenommeres, for example, can be found in the 
<taxonomicName box="[500,665,655,679]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Cratomorphini">Cratomorphini</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicName authority="Zaragoza-Caballero, 1995" authorityName="Zaragoza-Caballero" authorityYear="1995" box="[675,1138,655,680]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Aspisomoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[675,829,656,680]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">Aspisomoides</emphasis>
Zaragoza-Caballero, 
<number box="[1079,1138,655,679]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" value="1995.0">1995</number>
</taxonomicName>
. But 
<taxonomicName box="[1203,1301,657,680]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Memoan" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1203,1301,657,680]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">Memoan</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have many affinities with the 
<taxonomicName box="[362,502,692,716]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Amydetinae">Amydetinae</taxonomicName>
, such as continuous glow (
<emphasis box="[816,974,692,716]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">
e.g. 
<taxonomicName authority="Illiger, 1807" authorityName="Illiger" authorityYear="1807" box="[866,974,692,716]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Amydetes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Amydetes</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
Illiger, 
<number box="[1066,1124,692,716]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" value="1807.0">1807</number>
, at least some 
<taxonomicName authority="McDermott, 1964" authorityName="McDermott" authorityYear="1964" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Magnoculus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1297,1435,692,716]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">Magnoculus</emphasis>
McDermott, 
<number box="[297,356,727,751]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" value="1964.0">1964</number>
</taxonomicName>
; but also in the 
<taxonomicName box="[540,643,727,751]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Photinini">Photinini</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicName authority="Say, 1825" authorityName="Say" authorityYear="1825" box="[651,979,727,752]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Phausis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="reticulata">
<emphasis box="[651,856,728,752]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">Phausis reticulata</emphasis>
Say, 
<number box="[920,979,727,751]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" value="1825.0">1825</number>
</taxonomicName>
, although not in the other species of the genus); ventral approximate eyes (
<emphasis box="[563,603,765,788]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">e.g.</emphasis>
some 
<taxonomicName box="[689,828,764,788]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Magnoculus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[689,828,764,788]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">Magnoculus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but also in 
<taxonomicName authority="Jeng, 2007" authorityName="Jeng" authorityYear="2007" box="[990,1293,764,789]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Oculogryphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[990,1149,764,788]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">Oculogryphus</emphasis>
Jeng, 
<number box="[1234,1293,764,788]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" value="2007.0">2007</number>
</taxonomicName>
, which is a 
<taxonomicName authority="Incertae" authorityName="Incertae" box="[151,387,799,824]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">
Lampyridae 
<emphasis box="[295,387,801,824]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">incertae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sedis, and many 
<taxonomicName box="[586,704,799,823]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Lampyrini">Lampyrini</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[762,887,799,823]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Luciolinae">Luciolinae</taxonomicName>
); two para-sagital elevations on the prothorax, a notable feature of 
<taxonomicName box="[363,501,836,860]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Magnoculus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[363,501,836,860]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">Magnoculus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; a widespread deep puncture (
<emphasis box="[857,1045,836,860]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">
e.g. 
<taxonomicName box="[907,1045,836,860]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Magnoculus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Magnoculus</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
), which is present in the pronotal margins of many 
<taxonomicName box="[358,493,871,895]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Lampyrinae">Lampyrinae</taxonomicName>
taxa (e.g. 
<taxonomicName box="[621,746,871,895]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Pleotomini">Pleotomini</taxonomicName>
) but not in the 
<taxonomicName box="[934,1040,871,895]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Photinini">Photinini</taxonomicName>
; distinct pleuroventral suture (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">
e.g. 
<taxonomicName box="[151,258,908,932]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Amydetes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Amydetes</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[276,434,908,932]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Oculogryphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[276,434,908,932]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">Oculogryphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); aedeagus with rounded apices of phallus and parameres (
<emphasis box="[1128,1161,909,932]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">e.g</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[1179,1286,908,932]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Amydetes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1179,1286,908,932]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">Amydetes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); absence of tibial spurs, as in 
<taxonomicName box="[377,485,944,968]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Amydetes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[377,485,944,968]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">Amydetes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[554,693,944,968]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Magnoculus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[554,693,944,968]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">Magnoculus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(present on the 
<taxonomicName box="[902,1005,943,967]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Photinini">Photinini</taxonomicName>
studied to date, but also absent in 
<taxonomicName box="[151,310,980,1004]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Oculogryphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,310,980,1004]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">Oculogryphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Indeed, it could be a rather difficult task to distinguish a 
<taxonomicName box="[980,1115,980,1004]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Lampyrinae">Lampyrinae</taxonomicName>
from an 
<taxonomicName box="[1221,1362,980,1004]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Amydetinae">Amydetinae</taxonomicName>
; while the former have the wider morphological variability within 
<taxonomicName box="[854,992,1016,1040]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Lampyridae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[1007,1147,1016,1040]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Amydetinae">Amydetinae</taxonomicName>
, generally with complex antennae, can have “simple” antennae (some 
<taxonomicName authority="Laporte, 1833" authorityName="Laporte" authorityYear="1833" box="[681,916,1052,1076]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Vesta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[681,737,1053,1076]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">Vesta</emphasis>
Laporte, 
<number box="[856,916,1052,1076]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" value="1833.0">1833</number>
</taxonomicName>
); and the secondary pubescence – typical of 
<taxonomicName box="[151,254,1088,1112]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Photinini">Photinini</taxonomicName>
(undoubtly found at least in 
<taxonomicName authority="Laporte, 1833" authorityName="Laporte" authorityYear="1833" box="[577,809,1088,1112]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Ethra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[577,641,1088,1112]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">Ethra</emphasis>
Laporte, 
<number box="[749,809,1088,1112]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" value="1833.0">1833</number>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
